lish an alternative to Keynesianism through their welfare and development programs. Encouraging the fair trade of commodities and goods through microfinance, consumer boycotts, and corporate social responsibility, these programs emphasized decentralization, privatization, and entrepreneurship. Tehila Sasson tells the stories of the activists, economists, politicians, and businessmen who reimagined the marketplace as a workshop for global reform. She reveals how their ideas, though commonly associated with conservative neoliberal policies, were part of a nonprofit-driven endeavor by the liberal left to envision markets as autonomous and humanizing spaces, facilitating ethical relationships beyond the impersonal realm of the state.Drawing on dozens of newly available repositories from nongovernmental, international, national, and business archives, The Solidarity Economy reconstructs the political economy of these markets—from handicrafts and sugar to tea and coffee—shedding critical light on the postimperial origins of neoliberalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHumanitarian assistance, British. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aNon-governmental organizationszGreat Britain. 0aNonprofit organizationszGreat Britain. 0aPostcolonialism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / NGOs (Non-Governmental Organizations).2bisacsh  aActivists.  aAid.  aBader.  aBridge.  aBroader.  aBusiness.  aCampaign.  aCapitalism.  aCharity shops.  aCharity.  aChristian.  aCommonwealth.  aCommunity.  aCompanies.  aConsumers.  aConsumption.  aCountries.  aCountry.  aCrisis.  aDebt.  aDevelopment.  aEconomic.  aEconomists.  aEconomy.  aEmpire.  aEmployment.  aFair.  aFinancial.  aFood.  aGovernment.  aGrowth.  aHandicraft.  aImperial.  aIndustrial.  aIndustries.  aLabor.  aLabour.  aMarket.